page_id: In order to maintain some style and consistency across articles
page_title: we should have a set standard on which tense they should be written in. There is a tiny little mention in the MoS about this
page_ns: but it's not really official (or entirely clear for that matter). I think the community needs to agree to a standard and stick to it.

page_id: I think articles about things that exist "inside" the show's universe (characters
revision_id: etc.) should be written in the '''past tense'''. We're writing about events from 1983
timestamp: after all. Writing in the present tense reads like a plot summary
contributor_id: and reading about the history of a person or thing as if it is happening in real time is not customary and feels very strange. —[[User:80XPD|80XPD]] ([[User talk:80XPD|talk]]) 21:25

page_id: {{Headermain|right|text=[[The Upside Down|THE UPSIDE DOWN]]|size=23|bar-width=0}}[[File:Upside-Down-S2.png|left|210px|link=The Upside Down]]The '''Upside Down''' is an alternate dimension existing in parallel to the human world. Most
page_ns: flora and fauna present in the dimension are linked together in a hive mind controlled by the [[Mind Flayer]]
revision_id: essentially forming an enormous superorganism. A key component of this hive mind was a species of humanoid predators

page_ns: is a recurring character in the [[Season 1|first season]] of [[Stranger Things]] and a main character in the [[Season 2|second season]].
Will was abducted by the [[Demogorgon]] and taken into an alternate dimension dubbed the [[Upside Down]]. For a week
revision_id: Will evaded the creature while his family and friends desperately searched for him. Although he was eventually rescued and returned to normal life
timestamp: his time in the Upside Down left him with a mysterious connection to the alternate realm.

page_id: [[File:Stranger Things 1x06-Eleven's mental void.jpg|left|200px|link=The Void]]'''The Void''' is a visual representation of [[Eleven]]'s mind while using extrasensory perception to locate other entities in different locations to her own.
The Void appears as a vast endless expanse of nothingness. The floor is covered in a thin layer of water. It is completely empty
page_title: not including Eleven herself or whatever or whoever she is trying to locate.

page_id: {{Headermain|text=[[The Vanishing of Will Byers|THE VANISHING OF WILL BYERS]]|size=23|bar-width=0}}

[[File:The Vanishing of Will Byers S01-E01 SS 001.png|left|260px|link=The Vanishing of Will Byers]]"'''Chapter One: The Vanishing of Will Byers'''" is the first episode of [[Stranger Things|''Stranger Things'']]'' ''and the first episode of the [[Stranger Things/Season 1|first season]]. It was written and directed by the [[The Duffer Brothers|Duffer Brothers]] and premiered on [[Netflix]] on July 15
page_title: 2016 along with the rest of the season.

page_id: On his way home from a [[Mike Wheeler|friend]]'s house
page_title: young [[Will Byers|Will]] sees [[The Monster|something terrifying]]. Nearby
page_ns: a [[Gate|sinister secret]] lurks in the depths of a [[Hawkins National Laboratory|government lab]].

page_title: though the term "Key" was also colloquially used to refer to the Gates themselves. When activated using two special keys
page_ns: the machine fired a high-powered laser beam which could open "a doorway between worlds".

factoids: The boys are searching for Will on Mirkwood when Mike sees a figure in the middle of the road. He tries to avoid it
column10: causing Lucas and Dustin to crash into him. Once he's back on his feet Mike shines his flashlight on the figure
column11: revealing it to be Eleven. A rumbling sound is heard from overhead
column12: making Mike look up at the sky. Joyce
column14: and Hopper are looking up too. Dark silhouetted clouds roll in above the town
column15: and blue lightning illuminates the sky.

page_title: saying “The storm is no longer coming. It's here.”

page_id: [[Stranger Things]] is a television-format series created by the [[The Duffer Brothers|Duffer Brothers]] released as a [[Netflix]] original series on July 15
The show takes place in the fictional town of [[Hawkins]]
page_title: [[Indiana]] in the early-to-mid 1980s. The [[Season 1|first season]] revolves around the disappearance of [[Will Byers]]
page_ns: while the [[Season 2|second season explores]] the repercussions of the mysterious events of season 1. The upcoming [[Season 3|third season]] will be focusing on "forces of evil that are new."

page_id: What makes an antagonist? Is Lucas an antagonist
page_title: for getting into a fight with Mike? Is Lonnie an antagonist
page_ns: for being a deadbeat? Is Joyce's boss an antagonist for almost denying her advances on her paycheck? Is Mr Scott's date an antagonist for giving him the cold shoulder?

page_id: Maybe Brenner has ends that justify the means. Is the Monster truly an antagonist
page_title: or is it just eating to survive?

page_id: Calling someone an antagonist is purely a subjective moral judgement in some cases. I'm not sure it's a valid category
page_title: and there's definitely not a unifying factor about everyone being called an antagonist here that ties them together
page_ns: which is kinda the point of a category. [[w:User:FishTank|FishTank]] <staff /> ([[w:Message Wall:FishTank|wall]]) 03:07

factoids: : I vote to keep. In this case it's not a purely subjective moral judgement
column10: but rather explains the characters' function in the story. Is Brenner pure evil? Is the monster? Perhaps not
column11: but that's not what the term means in the context of narrative. It just means that they're the opposition - the ones who stand in the way of the protagonists reaching their goal. Stranger Things is a story that distinguishes between the protagonists and antagonists very clearly

factoids: : I vote to keep as well
column10: for more or less the same reason as 80XPD: An antagonist is
column12: a character that functions as an obstacle that the protagonist needs to overcome
column13: and the division between protagonists and antagonists in Stranger Things are pretty clear cut. The fact that you can justify the actions of an antagonist and maybe even sympathize with them does not make them any less of an antagonist
column14: it just makes for better storytelling (as does protagonists not always getting along
column15: as in the case with Lucas). [[User:Savemejebus|SaveMeJebus]] ([[User talk:Savemejebus|talk]]) 08:26
